# Root README Standard: Workshop Landing Article

The root `README.md` is the first artifact many readers will see. It should read like a Red Hat technical article for a product demo, not like an installation runbook.

The document must explain the enterprise platform pattern:
- Why regulated organizations need trusted AI development platforms.
- How private local models and governed external models can coexist.
- How Red Hat products package, integrate, and operate the platform capabilities.
- How open source projects provide the innovation foundation.
- How each workshop step contributes to the complete story.

## Required Structure

Use this structure unless there is a strong reason not to:

```markdown
# Trusted Enterprise AI Development Platform on Red Hat OpenShift AI

## Why This Workshop Exists

## Architecture

![RHOAI coding demo layered capability map](docs/assets/architecture/rhoai-capability-map.svg)

## What We Are Building

## What The Demo Proves

## How Red Hat And Open Source Make It Work

## Red Hat Products Demonstrated

## Open Source Projects You Will Meet

## Trust Boundaries

## Why This Is Worth Knowing

## Running The Workshop

## Repository Map

## Demo Personas

## References
```

Operational content is allowed, but it must come after the architecture and learning narrative.

The root README is not a runbook. Keep detailed deployment operations in `docs/OPERATIONS.md` and recovery procedures in `docs/TROUBLESHOOTING.md`. Do not claim capabilities that the repo does not implement. Label future or deferred capabilities clearly, and make trust boundaries, external services, credentials, and data movement visible.

## Red Hat Product Demo Requirements

The root README must include a clear Red Hat product map. At minimum, cover products currently used by the repo:

- Red Hat OpenShift
- Red Hat OpenShift AI
- Red Hat OpenShift GitOps
- Red Hat OpenShift Dev Spaces
- Migration Toolkit for Applications
- Developer Lightspeed for MTA
- Red Hat Developer Hub
- Red Hat Connectivity Link
- Red Hat build of Keycloak, when identity brokering is part of the flow

For each product, describe its role in the workshop. The reader should understand why this is a Red Hat platform demo.

## Open Source Education Requirements

The root README must include an open source project map. Explain how upstream projects fit into the Red Hat product/platform story.

Common projects in this repo:
- Open Data Hub and models-as-a-service
- KServe
- vLLM
- llm-d
- Gateway API
- Kuadrant and Authorino
- Eclipse Che and DevWorkspace
- Continue and OpenCode
- Konveyor
- Backstage

The open source section should educate, not only list links.

## Trust Boundary Requirements

The root README must include an explicit trust boundary table or equivalent explanation.

Required distinction:
- Private local models keep prompts/code within the OpenShift platform boundary.
- Governed external models are centrally controlled through MaaS but still process prompts outside the platform.

Never imply that all model paths are private when external models are included.

## Synchronization Rules

Keep the root README synchronized with the repo:
- Stage table must match actual `stages/` directories and `demo/flows/default.yaml`.
- Deploy command list must match actual stage directories.
- Repository map must match actual layout.
- Product list must match major Red Hat products actually used.
- References must include official Red Hat docs/product pages for products mentioned.

## Architecture Diagram Convention

The root README includes an SVG architecture diagram under a `## Architecture` heading. The diagram is placed **after** "Why This Workshop Exists" and **before** "What We Are Building" — the reader understands the motivation first, sees the platform map, then reads the details.

- The diagram lives at `docs/assets/architecture/rhoai-capability-map.svg`.
- Use a markdown image reference: `![RHOAI coding demo layered capability map](docs/assets/architecture/rhoai-capability-map.svg)`
- Do not place the diagram at the top of the file or before the title.

## Style Rules

- Blog-like prose first, operations second.
- Use sequential heading levels.
- Use `-` for unordered lists.
- Use fenced code blocks with language identifiers.
- Prefer SVG architecture diagrams from `docs/assets/architecture/` over inline ASCII diagrams.
- Keep the root README concise enough to be readable; use stage READMEs for depth.

## Agent Behavior

After modifying the root README:
- Verify no literal "Tell:" or "Show:" labels remain.
- Verify product map and open source map are present.
- Verify trust boundary language is precise.
- Verify deploy commands and step links match the repo.
- Run `git diff --check`.
